00:01:06.099 --> 00:01:11.400
we want things to finish sooner. So if we run it sequentially, it's going to finish

00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:16.680
tomorrow. But if we can parallelize, it's finished today. And we typically go to our

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:21.599
local computer and say, I'm going to use my different course here. Distributed computing

00:01:21.599 --> 00:01:28.120
is basically you want to reach out to more machines and parallelize over those. And I

00:01:28.120 --> 00:01:33.800
do want to mention that synchronous programming and processing, it's related to parallel processing

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:38.760
and the most common use case that people might know here is if you have a shiny application

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:44.080
and there is a button and you click on that button, and that needs to run a lot of computation

00:01:44.080 --> 00:01:47.800
and it would take a long time before it's finished, you don't want your user interface

00:01:47.800 --> 00:01:53.400
to freeze up. So you want to run that in the background in parallel. And the future framework

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:57.739
