Another thing is what operating system should I support? Today, I only need Linux. But maybe

00:04:03.300 --> 00:04:08.940
next year, someone will ask to support Windows or you get collaborators on Windows or Mac.

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:12.979
So you start thinking about that on day one when you start. You don't want to think about

00:04:12.979 --> 00:04:18.859
these things, but you have to. Will it scale? It runs on my local machine. What if we get

00:04:18.859 --> 00:04:26.660
96 cores? Will it work? Will it work on five machines and so on? And do I need to maintain

00:04:26.739 --> 00:04:31.459
several code bases? We already saw that example in the previous talk, where typically, people

00:04:31.459 --> 00:04:37.980
have sequential code. And by adding support for parallel code, it's very common to say,

00:04:37.980 --> 00:04:43.779
if not parallel, run the sequential or run some parallel version of it.

00:04:43.779 --> 00:04:47.940
So now you have two code bases you have to maintain. You have to figure out test coverage

00:04:47.940 --> 00:04:55.899
for those and twice the risk for bugs, basically. So questions like this you have. And then

00:04:55.899 --> 00:05:00.019
when you tried everything, you might actually end up in everything works for you and then

00:05:00.019 --> 00:05:05.100
there is some user. It didn't work for me because some global variable wasn't handled.

00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:11.859
So that's where the future framework and the future package comes in. It's tried to take

00:05:11.859 --> 00:05:18.619
away all those things. You don't have to worry about them. It's a simple unifying solution

00:05:18.619 --> 00:05:28.100
for parallel APIs in R. The motto is write once, run anywhere. 100% cross-platform. It's

00:05:28.100 --> 00:05:33.980
installed super easily in all packages, so you don't have to worry about that. I claim

00:05:33.980 --> 00:05:41.459
it's very well tested. It's got lots of CPU mileage and used in production. And it's meant

00:05:41.459 --> 00:05:49.339
to be so things just work. There will be corner cases, but they can be fixed. But most

00:05:49.339 --> 00:05:56.940
of the time, it will just work. So I need to tell you a little bit about the

00:05:56.940 --> 00:06:02.380
core of this. So if you peek into MCL Apply, Parallel Apply, ForEach, and a lot of other

00:06:02.380 --> 00:06:10.140
solutions, they have in principle three things in common, three building blocks. And we pulled

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:15.940
out those concepts into the future package. So one is you have an R expression, and you

00:06:15.940 --> 00:06:21.700
want to run that in parallel. So there's a function in the package future called future

00:06:21.700 --> 00:06:28.500
that you say, take this expression, run it in parallel, and keep a track of it in a handle.

00:06:28.500 --> 00:06:35.100
And then you can go to that thing in the background and say, are you done? You call resolve, done,

00:06:35.100 --> 00:06:38.820
true, false, true, false. And depending on the answer, in your code, you can do different

00:06:38.820 --> 00:06:43.579
things. And of course, at the end of the day, you want the value from this expression to

00:06:43.579 --> 00:06:48.459
come back to you. So that's a function called value. And if it's not done yet, it will wait

00:06:48.459 --> 00:06:53.059
until it's done. So these three constructs are very powerful.

00:06:53.059 --> 00:06:58.140
And I didn't invent them. This came up in the mid-'70s by different groups. And it's

00:06:58.140 --> 00:07:06.299
been studied in computer science. That's where the term future was coined.

00:07:06.299 --> 00:07:13.739
So with these things, we can now build our first parallel LApply. And this code works.

00:07:13.739 --> 00:07:18.459
It shows the gist of the idea. The real thing, you want to do a little bit more bells and

00:07:18.459 --> 00:07:27.540
whistles beneath the hood. But it works. So the idea here is instead of calling this

00:07:28.140 --> 00:07:34.420
function on each element as is in your current session, you just spawn it off as a future

00:07:34.420 --> 00:07:41.140
in parallel. So you get a list of futures here, handles to those. And then in the end

00:07:41.140 --> 00:07:44.420
of your function, you say, give me the values of this, because that's what I'm interested

00:07:44.420 --> 00:07:49.019
in, and return. And what happens behind the scenes, the workers will start working on

00:07:49.019 --> 00:07:54.859
the futures when they're available. And this runs in parallel.

00:07:54.859 --> 00:08:02.140
So these are very powerful building blocks, I say. And it allows you, if you want to

